EmailTemplate.subject: Live Different Academy: Acceptance Email
EmailTemplate.textOnly:
Hey {!Contact.FirstName}!
On behalf of everyone here at Live Different I would like to welcome you to the Live Different Academy. We look forward to meeting you in person and having you with us this coming year as we work together to make a difference in Mexico!
My name is Jenn and I am the Academy and Live Different Build Administrator. I am very excited to work with you this year to prepare you for your 4 month journey with us!
Attached Information to Read Over:
Fundraising Tips and Ideas - This is a list of past fundraising ideas that other volunteers found successful. Use your Canada Helps Page for making, entering and requesting donations or payments related to your trip. You can share (email, Facebook, etc.) your Canada Helps Page with any potential donors so they can donate online to your Live Different Build project (to help meet your fundraising goal).
Presentation Letter - For businesses to learn what you will be doing with us if you are asking for donations.
Consent Package - These forms need to be filled out, then scanned and emailed back to me.
Child Protection Policy - This is for all our Live Different Academy students to read. It is our policy on what is appropriate behaviour when dealing with minors and the steps that we take to protect them.
Child Protection Policy Agreement - Once you have read the above Child Protection Policy, please sign the agreement, then scan and email it back to me.
Packing List - Suggested packing list if you have no idea what to bring with you!
Criminal Record Check (through mybackcheck) - If you are 18 years of age as of January 1st, 2014, you will be required to obtain a criminal record check. Please obtain one either through your local police station, or you can ask me to send you an online link.
Personal Response Questions and References - Completing this online form will help us gain a better understanding of who you are and why you want to participate with us. We also ask that you provide us with two personal references who have known you for at least two years. To complete this form, click on the link below. https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1f6nhUFf7SMHJ6R39pFrk2fCvYsV-Ww4OMekTPFBtWRQ/viewform
Tuition/Payment: Here is your payment breakdown:
$5,995 - Tuition Total
$300 - Initial Deposit, upon registration (paid directly to Live Different) July 30, 2014 - $2,695 - Academy Tuition (paid directly to Live Different) September 30, 2014 - $3,000 - Academy Charitable project costs (donations that can receive a tax receipt through your Canada Helps fundraising page)
Flights:
Please book your flights to and from the San Diego Airport
Airport Code: SAN Arrival: September 14, 2014 Departure: December 13, 2014
Schedule:
September 14th - Fly to San Diego, CA (Airport Code: SAN) September 15th - Drive down to Vicente Guerrero, Baja California, Mexico. September 16th - Orientation September - December December 10/11th - Graduation for our Academy program. December 12th - Drive up to San Diego, CA. December 13th - All students fly home from San Diego, CA.
Learning in Mexico
The "Week in a Life" Experience: This week is a major highlight of our Academy program! During "A week in a life" our students build their own 'Shack' made from materials that they collect. During this time, our students participate in typical jobs of a local Mexican labourer and experience life from a different perspective. This includes, but is not limited to, working in the local fields, rock picking, clamming and cleaning work. (See below for more information on the jobs.) You get paid what a local day labourer supporting a family would, and then you have to 'pay bills.' You cook all your own meals with whatever you can afford to buy, do your own washing by hand, and live without technology. Shack week will change you!
Clamming: This job is done at different times of the day, depending on the tide. You go out into the water with a pitchfork and collect as many clams at you can. This job can be very difficult as it can be cold water, and can be at night if the tides work that way. As you start to collect clams, it becomes a very rewarding job! Working in the Fields: This is a very long and enlightening day. You will work in either the berry, tomato or onion fields doing picking, pruning, weeding, sorting...the list goes on! Getting to work alongside local labourers is a real highlight of this job. Rock picking: As you collect rocks, they need to be sorted according to color, size and shape. Your boss will let you know what you are collecting and is not shy when it comes to throwing back ones that are not right.
Volunteering: We do a lot of volunteering in our local community, up to two - three times each week. We love it! Our opportunities have been based in schools, a community centre and local organizations.
Teaching: We spend time in schools helping teach English and play with the children. You will plan and teach lessons on a range of topics including colours, animals, numbers and greetings. This is a great way to get to know some great children and know you are making a difference in their lives. Seniors home: This is often one of the most popular volunteering opportunities. You will be spending time with the elderly in the community and helping out with different jobs such as prepping meals, gardening and painting nails. These elderly people are so lovely and really enjoy spending time with us. Community centre: We will be running an Art program for kids in our local community which has been really successful in the past! You get to sit alongside some awesome children and paint, bead, collage and do other arty things!
Chores: You get to live in a very nice and large house in Mexico and we like to look after it. We make a cleaning schedule that rotates jobs, and everyone also gets a turn at cooking dinner for the group in the week. Don't worry if you aren't a confident chef as there is plenty of room for learning. We also learn a lot about Mexican dishes from our amazing Live Different Build cook. Chores are done daily to ensure we look after the house and property well. Don't worry, they aren't hard chores. Daily Classes: Class time is either in the morning or afternoon. It usually consists of 2 hours of discussion, hands on activities, enlightening videos and creativity. These are usually done 4 or 5 days a week and sometimes contain an activity/research for homework that will tie into the next lesson. You will get to learn a lot through our Social Justice curriculum on topics such as poverty, slavery, corporations, leadership and what to do with all of this when you return home. You will also get to study a couple of books that touch on these topics. You will learn and grow in so many ways through the activities and discussions in this course! Spanish Lessons: You will be taking 2 weeks of intensive introductory Spanish lessons in Ensenada at the beginning of your time in Mexico. This will help you communicate and build relationships with people in the community even quicker! Excursions and exploring: You will get the chance to go and see a bit of our local area in and beyond Vicente Guerrero. Our weekends often involve going somewhere different like the beach, volcano, cafe, mountains, etc. We give you a lot of down time and we make suggestions for this to be spent in the community, meeting new people and building relationships.
Building Projects: While in Mexico you will get to be a part of a house build with your Academy team. This is an amazing experience! You will learn a lot of building skills and also get to build relationships with a family, and the community.
Living in Mexico
Independence: Your time in Mexico is a valuable part of your experience with our Live Different Academy, because it is your time to get to know your peers, learn new skills and challenge yourself with new and exciting experiences. During this time you will grow in your independence as you find your way around, have to prepare your own meals and live in our housing with some great people. Time Management: You are responsible for waking up in the morning on time for orientation, classes, and preparing meals. Set that alarm! Developing a Budget: You must budget for a few weekend activities, evening hangouts, and souvenirs that you wish to purchase. Plan accordingly! Household Responsibilities: No one wants to live in a dirty house! Our staff is there to help you and to make sure that our house is a place we can all enjoy. Everyone has their chores and they are expected to do them. Our staff will help you learn any new housekeeping skills you may not yet have. Budgeting and Preparing Meals: You are responsible for your helping our staff members shop for groceries and plan some meals. Think about how much fun you will have planning your very own menu, creating a grocery list, and sticking to it at the store! Laundry and Showers: Our housing has washing machines for your use, as well as sufficient bathroom and shower facilities. Our staff will teach you about how to use our machines. You will understand and value the concept of the 'power showers' in Mexico to conserve water while living in the desert! Sharing Rooms and Respecting Personal Space: Need we say more? Living with others: When we consider others, we are creating a better living space for ourselves as well. Living with others can be challenging or fun - you choose how you will embrace it. Some people need more people time and some need space. Be mindful of what someone else values and you will love your time here.
Photos, Blogs and Updates: Please check out our Live Different Facebook page to see what our current Academy students are up to. It will help you prepare for your year with us! https://www.facebook.com/pages/Live-Different/189864944417296?ref=hl
Please feel free to call or email me to answer any questions that you or your parents may have. I am always available to you at the contact information below. Please do not be shy in calling or emailing; if you don't know, just ask. I'm here to help.
Sincerely,
Jenn
Jenn Digiandomenico Programs Administrator jenn@livedifferent.com
